The Rational Root Theorem states that if a polynomial has integer coefficients, then any rational root can be expressed as a fraction $\dfrac{p}{q}$ (\textit{rational root} means that the fraction $\dfrac{p}{q}$ is irreducible), where $p$ is a integer factor of the final term, and $q$ is a factor of the coefficient of the highest degree term. <end think> {eq}p = 1\cdots, \pm 1, \pm 3, \pm 5, \pm 15, \cdots

q = 1\cdots -9, 1, \cdots

{/eq} We have \begin{align*} &\dfrac{\pm 1}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 1}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 1}{9}, \dfrac{\pm 1}{3}, \dfrac{\pm 1}{1}

\\ &\dfrac{\pm 3}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 3}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 3}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 3}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 3}{1}

\\ &\dfrac{\pm 5}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 5}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 5}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 5}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 5}{1}

\\ &\dfrac{\pm 15}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 15}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 15}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 15}{1}, \dfrac{\pm 15}{1}

\end{align*} We can have $\boxed{16}$ different possible roots.
